    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev I Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>5 Inangti<add>?</add> Hackney</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <date>29 June / 43</date>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I write to you<lb/> in the shape of a note be<lb/>cause I am anxious
                to forward<lb/> you two poems by the same<lb/> post and for the same postage<lb/>
                and as I have but little in<lb/>teresting to communicate the<lb/> apparent brevity
                of my epistle<lb/> you will I trust kindly excuse</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I owe you an apology<lb/> for not having answered your<lb/> kind
                favor of <date>10 January</date> long<lb/> ere this, but continued
                indis<lb/>position since the early part<lb/> of <date>March</date> and a very
                long<lb/> task of writing which I had<lb/> to finish as speedily as possible<lb/>
                prevented my addressing any<lb/> of my correspondents and <add>?</add></p>
            <p
                rend="The following (page 5) is written in the opposite direction over the above text."/>
            <p>where you have any money in hand for<lb/> me. Do not procure them till<add>?</add>
                you can pay yourself<lb/> from any money you may have to transmit<lb/> to me &amp;
                then I should be obliged by your<lb/> forwarding them by the first opportunity I
                think<lb/> my name had better be written in them or they<lb/> will not pass without
                a <hi rend="underline">fine</hi> which I have no in<lb/>clination to pay. Papa
                begged me to inform<lb/> you he had a small parcel for you from the <persName>Miss<lb/>
                    <add>?</add></persName> which he will forward by the first opportunity</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Trusting this letter will find you in<lb/> health &amp; prosperity
                    <add>?</add> in all your undertakings</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I remain dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Grace Aguilar</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>2</p>
            <p>I trust plead my excuse with<lb/> you as with others. Allow me<lb/> to thank you for
                the 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> number<lb/> of your periodical, which my<lb/> brother
                brought me from <persName>Mr Franklin</persName><lb/> without however any message,
                so<lb/> I do not know whether you sent<lb/> any with it and also let me<lb/> thank
                you, for the very grati<lb/>fying notice with which you<lb/> introduce my little
                poem “The<lb/> Chambers of the Dying” to your<lb/> readers, in your second
                number.<lb/> I trust the poems I send may<lb/> prove suitable and acceptable<lb/>
                the intent of both is to bring<lb/> us closer to the gracious Saviours<lb/> of
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName>, than is often unhappily<lb/> the case with our
                nation. They<lb/> generally place Him at a<lb/> distance. I never think of
                deriving<lb/> comfort from the fact that He<lb/> knows &amp; loves us better
                than<lb/> our dearest Friends on Earth, &amp; feels</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>3</p>
            <p>and shares every pang His Love<lb/> inflicts. The Hour of peace is<lb/> simply to rob
                Death of its gloom<lb/> Oh that Immortality were more<lb/> thought of amongst us,
                than it is!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I regret not yet having had<lb/> time to read your periodical<lb/>
                with sufficient attention to pass<lb/> an opinion upon it. You have<lb/> however my
                very best wishes<lb/> for its success, as its design is<lb/> praiseworthy and the
                labour<lb/> to yourself must I think be very<lb/> great. My Father begs I<lb/> will
                deliver you his kind regards<lb/> and our united thanks for the<lb/> detailed
                account of the books, which<lb/> your last favor contained. I trust<lb/> ere this,
                you have received<lb/> some returns from the different<lb/> places to which they
                have been<lb/> sent. In <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> &amp; <placeName>St
                    Thomas</placeName><lb/> I know they have had some<lb/> sale, as the fact has
                    <sic>travelled</sic></p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>4</p>
            <p>to us in <placeName>England</placeName>. I do not<lb/> much understand business
                my<lb/>self, <del>but</del> so that the slowness of<lb/> payment appears to me
                rather<lb/> strange. You are right in sup<lb/>posing gain was not my object<lb/> in
                publishing the work, but yet<lb/> I am not rich or even independent<lb/> enough, not
                to feel anxious to<lb/> receive that, which if the books<lb/>
                <del>are sold</del> or even some of them <del>have</del> are<lb/> sold at the places
                to which they<lb/> have been sent, must be my<lb/> due an anxiety which I have<lb/>
                no doubt you can <hi rend="underline">understand</hi><lb/> but I know it is not in
                your<lb/> power to <sic>remidy</sic> it. You will<lb/> oblige me greatly however
                by<lb/> urging your agents to a settlement<lb/> for those they have sold. With<lb/>
                regard to <persName>Dr Channings<add>?</add></persName> works<lb/> which you say can
                be procured<lb/> in 5 vols for 4 Dollars—I<lb/> should like much to have them</p>
        </body>
